’ 5 25 C. Flaminio: the chief popular leader of his day, often held up to reproach by writers, like Cicero, of aristocratic sympathies. The reproach was enhanced by his disgraceful blunder in the battle of Lake Trasimenus, B.C. 217, in which his army was cut to pieces and he him- self killed. In spite of his ill repute as a demagogue, and his military failure‚ Flaminius was the author of some very salutary measures. In his tribunate, B.C. 232, he carried the law here referred tc, dividing the Gallie and Picene territory among poor citizens, — the policy afterwards revived by the Gracchi, and perhaps the most hopeful remedy of the evils of the State.
